[normal]Further submission from [bold]Eastern Shires Purchasing Organisation[bold]Follow up note to [bold]o[bold]ral evidence provided by ESPO 4[bold]th[bold] November[bold]‘
[normal]What is ESPOs estimate of the scale of savings potentially deliverable through [bold]improved collaboration in procurement?[bold]’
[normal]Preamble 
[normal]As the committee may be aware there have been 
[normal]a number of 
[normal]empirical and qualitative studies on 
[normal]the subject matter of collaboration and savings potential pan public sector
[normal]. The common 
[normal]conclusions 
[normal]are often
[normal] the recognition of
[normal] variability 
[normal]in potential 
[normal]across expenditure categories, the relative ‘starting positions’ across local government and
[normal] the willingness/fitness
[normal] for purpose of collaboration in a range of circumstances
[normal] all impacting the assessment
[normal]. 
[normal]ESPO believes that as well as the typical understanding of the term ‘savings’  as an improved price point via collaboration, it is important to recognise the broader, sometimes hidden costs. These include the cost of undertaking procurement itself, the value of enhanced management information to guide strategic decision making and the cost avoidance that is associated with costs of poor procurement.
[normal]As a result of this complex context 
[normal]ESPO deliberately does not make a ‘savings promise’ 
[normal]such as a return for every pound spent through its procurement solutions. I
[normal]nstead 
[normal]the demonstration of value is in positive 
[normal]engage
[normal]ment 
[normal]with local government
[normal] to
[normal] understand opportunity and act as a delivery 
[normal]agent for realising it. The case study below is an example of this approach which has delivered a saving of circa 4% on a major area of LG expenditure.
[normal]Case Study: A National Framework for Temporary Staff (MSTAR) [bold]Background
[normal]In
[normal] April 2011
[normal] 
[normal]an
[normal] 
[normal]ESPO led 
[normal]Pro5 framework 
[normal]agreement for the supply chain management for the provision of t
[normal]emporary 
[normal](agency) labour
[normal] was 
[normal]established 
[normal]by ESPO a
[normal]s a replacement for a previous localised contract. The contract was let to cover a four year period.
[normal]One of the drivers was that t
[normal]he Local Government Professional Services Group (LGPSG) had been tasked with exploring best practices and identifying and establishing procurement solutions
[normal] in this market
[normal]. The LGPSG identified the need for a national framework for temporary staffing to be established by local government for local government. 
[normal]Pro5
[normal] were asked to run such a procurement exercise and through consultation with our Pro5 partners, ESPO agreed to lead the
[normal] procurement
[normal] exercise.
[normal]The key drivers for establishing the new framework were
[normal]:
[normal]The Department for Education (DfE) w
[normal]as
[normal] also exploring the potential for reducing significant spend in
[normal] the Education staffing arena. 
[normal]Schools had similar pressures to local government and the wider public sector in facing budget cuts, whilst being expected to deliver services; coupled with the essential requirement to ensure 
[normal]the 
[normal]safeguarding of children.  The DfE was very keen to join this collaborative process and wished to include its requirements into the overall solution.  
[normal]An exte
[normal]nsive procurement project followed with
[normal] emphasis on aspects which were identified as being key: project management, collaboration/consultation, and communication. The project was completed over a period of 12 months and a framework established with 11 suppliers covering 6 lots offering neutral and master vendor solutions. The framework 
[normal]is 
[normal]known as MSTAR (Managed Services for Temporary Agency Resources).
[normal]ESPO has established and continues to undertake a robust framework management programme. Regular supplier and customer engagement activities are carried out and management information is captured and presented to stakeholders on a quarterly basis via e-mail newsletters and the Local Government Association Knowledge Hub.
[normal]Savings
[normal]Under the MSTAR framework there is a wide selection of management information received from suppliers. This covers the core elements relating to contract spend and savings achieved
[normal] as a result of paying lower agency margins
[normal], and also the finer details ranging from invoice accuracy to hours process
[normal]ed
[normal] against each job category. The 
[normal]data reuirement
[normal] arose from the initial MSTAR tender, where ESPO engaged with 
[normal]its
[normal] stakeholders to establish what information would be useful and required by the parties. 
[normal]M
[normal]anagement information is received from suppliers on a quarterly basis, against the financial year, and ESPO then collate and analyse this
[normal] information by way of contract 
[normal]management.
[normal] 
[normal]Based on the management information received, the collective spend across all customers is 
[normal]already 
[normal]£434.8m[bold] and the collective savings are 
[normal]£19.9m[bold]. This information covers the life of the framework to date (April 2011 to October 2013).
